The paper discusses the use of data analytics and graph visualization techniques to analyze scholarly publications and journals. This involves scraping data from Google Scholar, which is a digital library of scholarly articles. The paper also mentions the computation of scholastic indicators for journals and the use of an econometric model to compute the journals' "Internationality" Index. Based on this information, the most likely sub-categories are cs.DL (Digital Libraries), cs.IR (Information Retrieval), cs.DB (Databases), cs.SI (Social and Information Networks), and cs.SD (Software Engineering).
